    <p><strong>Abstract.</strong> One-dimensional self-gravitating systems admit thermodynamical equilibria. Tep et al. (2026) use an exact collision-driven integrator to measure long-term relaxation times of several 1D equilibrium families (Plummer, Compact, Harmonic, and Anharmonic). The key result is that fully degenerate (harmonic) systems relax on a timescale scaling as N²t_dyn, much slower than the N t_dyn scaling predicted by quasilinear kinetic theory.</p>

    <h2>Key findings</h2>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Harmonic systems:</strong> trel ∝ N² t_dyn (very slow thermalization). See <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.11238">the paper</a> and Figure 2.</li>
      <li><strong>Partially degenerate systems:</strong> two regimes — N² scaling at low N, transitioning to N scaling at large N as the fraction of non-degenerate orbits increases (Figure 3).</li>
      <li><strong>Non-degenerate systems (Plummer, Compact):</strong> trel ∝ N t_dyn; compact support increases the prefactor (quasi-kinetic blocking).</li>
      <li><strong>Theoretical implication:</strong> Balescu–Lenard and related quasilinear kinetic theories fail for flat-frequency profiles; thermodynamic blocking and non-quasilinear effects must be considered.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>Implications</h2>
    <p>This work implies that dynamically degenerate cores (e.g., harmonic-like density cores in dwarf galaxies) may remain out of equilibrium for much longer than standard kinetic theory predicts, with potential consequences for dynamical friction and the survival of cores.</p>

    <h2>References</h2>
    <ol>
      <li id="ref1">Tep, K.; Fouvry, J.-B.; Pichon, C. (2026). "Very long-term relaxation of harmonic 1D self-gravitating systems." arXiv:2603.11238. <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.11238">https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.11238</a></li>
      <li>Roule, M.; Fouvry, J.-B., et al. (2022). Quasi kinetic blocking (discussed in text).</li>
      <li>Deme, B. & Fouvry, J.-B. (2025). Thermodynamic blocking (perspective cited).</li>
    </ol>

